      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001_21",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Lemma 1. If x, y € G are nonzero orthogonal vectors, then *** is parallel to y.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5131578971644676,
          0.31540697699054715,
          0.9191729401572599,
          0.34449404757321006
        ],
        "order": 12
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001_22",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Proof. Put z = xx y # 0, so that x, y, and Z = X*y are nonzero and mutually orthogonal. Then w = xx z # 0, so w = x*z is nonzero and orthogonal to x and z. However, if (x**) xy #0, then w = x*(x*y) = (x**) *y = (x**) x y is also orthogonal to y, a contradiction.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5169172954630405,
          0.3573878061595335,
          0.9210526271215861,
          0.43030753985633696
        ],
        "order": 13
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0004",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001_7",
