      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2010_Solutions_2010s_page_001_12",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A-3 If a = b = 0, then the desired result holds trivially, so we assume that at least one of a,b is nonzero. Pick any point (ao, bo) € R', and let L be the line given by the parametric equation L(t) = (ao, bo) + (a,b)t fort € R. By the chain rule and the given equation, we have a(hoL) = hoL. If we write f = hoL: R → R, then f'(t) = f(t) for all t. It follows that f(t) =Ce' for some constant C. Since |f(t)| ≤ M for all t, we must have C = 0. It follows that hao, bo) = 0; since (ao, bo) was an arbitrary point, h is identically 0 over all of R?.",
        "bbox": [
          0.09586466560150368,
          0.6874999998833208,
          0.49060150770676686,
          0.8327261329988873
